⦿ .spun — the five-fold spin of The Grand Inquisitor
node BKZ · BKZ · ⟦The Grand Inquisitor:BKZ:b04bb7⟧

WHO   — The Grand Inquisitor — Ivan's poem · freedom vs bread
WHAT  — The novel's philosophical summit: the Inquisitor charges that humanity cannot bear freedom and craves ‘miracle, mystery, and authority,’ so the Church gave it bread and a master instead.
WHERE — BKZ · The Brothers Karamazov  Framework inputs: The Brothers Karamazov (Dostoevsky, 1880)  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)
WHY   — Because the case against Christ's gift of freedom had to be made overwhelming — and answered, devastatingly, by silence and a kiss.
HOW   — By an old man's long indictment of freedom, and a Christ who says nothing and kisses him on his bloodless lips.

awareness — what the node knows of itself:
  Men are weak and crave bread and a master, not the terrible freedom You gave them — and to my whole indictment You answer only with a kiss.

